name: Marines' Hymn
comments: The official hymn of the United States Marine Corps. The lyrics are said to date from the 19th century, however no pre-20th century text is known. The author of the lyrics is likewise unknown. Legend has it that a marine on duty in Mexico penned the hymn. The unknown author transposed the phrases in the motto on the flag of the United States Marine Corps so that the first two lines of the hymn would read: "From the Halls of Montezuma, to the Shores of Tripoli". It was adapted as such in 1929 with a minor change in lyrics approved in 1942. See also alleged author L. Z. Phillips .

name: На сопках Маньчжурии
comments: "On the Hills of Manchuria" is a waltz referring to an incident during the Battle of Mukden, the disastrous final land battle of the Russo-Japanese War, when the Mokshansky Infantry Regiment was encircled by Japanese forces for 11 days, during which it sustained considerable casualties. Shatrov dedicated the work to one of his comrades fallen at the battle. Soon after its publication, the poet Stepan Petrov, better known by the pen-name of Skitalets, provided the lyrics which contributed to its wider success. It was arranged in Finland by Johnny and Osmo Ruuskanen for a version by The Sounds [FI] and they are credited as composers by ISWC (T-316.768.423-9) and their version has been widely covered in Japan. The Finnish website consistently credits Ilya Alekseevich Shatrov as the original author
